Multivariate analysis

Introduction

In this tutorial, we will perform multivariate analysis on NMR data using the metabom8 package. We will cover Principal Component Analysis (PCA) and Orthogonal Partial Least Squares Discriminant Analysis (OPLS-DA). This analysis helps in understanding the underlying structure of the data and identifying differences between groups.

Prerequisites

Make sure you have the following libraries installed:

install.packages("metabom8")
install.packages("readr")
install.packages("ggplot2")

Setting Up the Environment

Lets set our working directory and load the necessary libraries.

setwd('/Volumes/AEIWZ A/Project/AG-Bio')
library(metabom8)
library(readr)
## Warning: package 'readr' was built under R version 4.2.3

library(ggplot2)

Loading the Data

We will load the NMR data, chemical shift values (ppm), and metadata from URLs:

# Load data
X = read.csv('https://raw.githubusercontent.com/KKUPhenomeCentre/ag-bio/main/src/data/leaf_norm.csv')
ppm = read.csv('https://raw.githubusercontent.com/KKUPhenomeCentre/ag-bio/main/src/data/leaf_ppm.csv')
meta = read.csv('https://raw.githubusercontent.com/KKUPhenomeCentre/ag-bio/main/src/data/Metadata.csv')

#Data cleaning
X = as.matrix(X)
colnames(X) = as.numeric(ppm)
# Convert ppm to numeric
ppm = as.numeric(ppm)

Visualizing Spectra

We can visualize the spectra to get an overview of the data:

matspec(X, ppm, shift = range(ppm), interactive = FALSE)

Setting Up for Analysis

For reproducibility, we will set a seed and prepare our data:

set.seed(180)

# Declare variables
Xn <- X  # PQN-normalised NMR data matrix
ppm <- ppm  # chemical shift vector in ppm
meta <- meta  # spectrometer metadata
an <- meta  # sample annotation

# Visualize first ten spectra
matspec(Xn[1:10,], ppm, shift = c(0, 10), interactive = FALSE)

Performing PCA

Now, we will perform PCA to reduce dimensionality and visualize the data:

# Perform PCA
pca_model = pca(X = Xn, pc = 2, scale = 'UV', center = TRUE)

# Plot PCA results: scores of the first two components
plotscores(obj = pca_model, pc = c(1, 2), an = list(Group = an$Class), title = 'PCA - Scores plot')

# Plot PCA loadings
plotload(mod = pca_model, pc = 1)  # 1st principal component

plotload(mod = pca_model, pc = 2)  # 2nd principal component

plotload(mod = pca_model, pc = 2, shift = c(6, 9))  # 2nd principal component in region 6-9 ppm

OPLS-DA Analysis

Next, we will perform OPLS-DA to classify the samples based on their classes:

# Get index of two classes
idx = an$Class %in% c('H+C', 'UH+D')

X = Xn[idx,]
Y = an$Class[idx]

# Filter NaN
X = na.omit(X)

# Train O-PLS model
opls.model = opls(X, Y)
## Performing discriminant analysis.
## Setting CV k-fold parameter to 3. Number of observations in group 1 is too low (n=3) for k=7.
## An O-PLS-DA model with 1 predictive and 1 orthogonal components was fitted.

# View model summary
opls.model@summary
##   PC_pred PC_orth  R2X AUROC AUROC_CV
## 1       1       1 0.52     1        1
## 2       1       2   NA     1        1
# Calculate model distances
distX = dmodx(mod = opls.model, plot = TRUE)

Plotting OPLS Scores

Now, we will visualize the OPLS scores:

plotscores(obj = opls.model, an = list(
  Group = an$Class[idx],          # Colour according to class
  Timepoint = an$Timepoint[idx]), # Timepoint can be ignored for this analysis
  title = 'OPLS - Scores plot',    # Plot title
  cv.scores = TRUE)                 # Visualize cross-validated scores

Plotting OPLS Loadings

We will also plot the loadings from the OPLS model:

plotload(opls.model, title = 'OPLS-DA Loadings', shift = c(0.5, 9.5))

Overlayed Spectra with Backscaled Loadings

Finally, we can visualize the overlayed spectra with backscaled loadings:

specload(mod = opls.model, shift = c(3.4, 3.8), an = list(
  facet = an$Class[idx]), 
  type = 'backscaled', 
  alp = 0.5, 
  title = 'Overlayed Spectra with Backscaled Loadings')
